entry.content:
In an <a href="http://www.debugrelease.com/2013/05/30/windows-azure-create-linux-virtual-machine-through-management-portal/">earlier post</a> I created a Linux virtual machine on Windows Azure. In this post I will show you how to establish a SSH connection to the virtual machine.

&nbsp;
<h4>Windows</h4>
Windows does not come with a SSH client but we can use <a href="http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html">PuTTY</a> to make SSH connections from a Windows machine.

Open putty.exe and enter host information as it is on the management portal.

&nbsp;

<a href="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/SNAGHTML3b92ce5e.png"><img style="background-image: none; padding-top: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin: 0px; display: inline; padding-right: 0px; border-width: 0px;" title="SNAGHTML3b92ce5e" alt="SNAGHTML3b92ce5e" src="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/SNAGHTML3b92ce5e_thumb.png" width="470" height="453" border="0" /></a>

&nbsp;

Click Open and you are asked to login. Enter username and password and you are logged into the Linux virtual machine.

&nbsp;

<a href="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/SNAGHTML3b9558d2.png"><img style="background-image: none; padding-top: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin: 0px; display: inline; padding-right: 0px; border-width: 0px;" title="SNAGHTML3b9558d2" alt="SNAGHTML3b9558d2" src="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/SNAGHTML3b9558d2_thumb.png" width="644" height="406" border="0" /></a>

&nbsp;
<h4>Linux Terminal</h4>
Logging into Linux virtual machine on Windows Azure from a Linux terminal is dead simple. Linux already comes with a OpenSSH client so there is nothing to be installed.

Just run the ssh command with correct port number and host. In my case the command is
<p class="text-info"><span>ssh –p 58473 azureuser@debrelubuntu.cloudapp.net</span></p>
&nbsp;

Enter the correct password when prompted and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob%27s_your_uncle">Bob’s your uncle</a>.

&nbsp;

<a href="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/image10.png"><img style="background-image: none; padding-top: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin: 0px; display: inline; padding-right: 0px; border-width: 0px;" title="image" alt="image" src="https://googledrive.com/host/0B6PDO8HPEQZNZWpTRms0ZWtlaUU/uploads/2013/05/image_thumb6.png" width="644" height="402" border="0" /></a>

It is a common feature of many apps to select photos stored on the device. The feature can be implemented by using PhotoChooserTask class. In this post I will show you how to use PhotoChooserTask to select existing photos and also take photos using the camera.

Code for this post is available on <a href="https://github.com/deepak-kapoor/photochooser">Github</a>.

The UI for this app is very simple. It contains just one Image control and a button

<pre class="font:courier-new lang:xhtml decode:true">&lt;StackPanel x:Name="ContentPanel" Grid.Row="1" Margin="12,0,12,0"&gt;
  &lt;Image x:Name="ImageChosen" /&gt;
  &lt;Button x:Name="ButtonChoosePhoto"
    Content="choose photo"
    Click="ButtonChoosePhoto_OnClick"/&gt;
&lt;/StackPanel</pre>

In the OnClick event handler I instantiate a PhotoChooserTask object, hook it with an event handler when Completed event is fired and finally call Show method on PhotoChooserTask.


<pre class="lang:c# decode:true " >private void ButtonChoosePhoto_OnClick(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
{
  PhotoChooserTask photoChooser = new PhotoChooserTask();
  photoChooser.Completed += photoChooser_Completed;
  photoChooser.Show();
}</pre> 


Within the event handler I place this code. The code checks if the TaskResult is OK and then creates a new BitmapImage object from the stream in PhotoResult object which is supplied as an argument to the handler.


<pre class="lang:c# decode:true " >void photoChooser_Completed(object sender, PhotoResult e)
{
  if (e.TaskResult == TaskResult.OK)
  {
    BitmapImage bitmap = new BitmapImage();
    bitmap.SetSource(e.ChosenPhoto);
    ImageChosen.Source = bitmap;
  }
}</pre> 


Here is the app in working.

